A drag stream nests event observables: pointerdown becomes the outer trigger, switchMap opens an inner pointermove stream, and takeUntil closes it on pointerup. switchMap is essential — it cancels any prior inner stream when a new pointerdown arrives, preventing overlapping drags.

```typescript
import { fromEvent, Observable, switchMap, takeUntil, map } from "rxjs";

interface DragPoint { x: number; y: number; }

export function drag$(el: HTMLElement): Observable<DragPoint> {
  const down$ = fromEvent<PointerEvent>(el, "pointerdown");
  const move$ = fromEvent<PointerEvent>(window, "pointermove");
  const up$ = fromEvent<PointerEvent>(window, "pointerup");
  return down$.pipe(
    switchMap(() => move$.pipe(
      map((e: PointerEvent): DragPoint => ({ x: e.clientX, y: e.clientY })),
      takeUntil(up$)
    ))
  );
}
```

The pipeline debounces keystrokes, drops duplicates with distinctUntilChanged, and switchMaps into a per-query observable that uses shareReplay({ bufferSize: 1 }) so repeated lookups for the same term reuse the buffered response. A Map<string, Observable<T>> persists the shared observables between queries.

